Rating: 4
The ease of making this dish plus the end results have made this a cold weather, comfort-food favorite here at my house. I have served it to kids, picky eaters and foodies alike, all of whom enjoyed it! Like most braised beef recipes, I actually like to make this one day ahead and refrigerate overnight, removing most of the coagulated fat from the top before reheating over low heat. Like others have suggested, browning the meat first also adds a nice depth to the flavors in this dish. The addition of diced carrots (2 medium) also melds nicely.

Rating: 4
This recipe is beyond wonderful!! Am much indebted to suggestions of previous reviewers, and have a couple to add: 1) I doubled the amt. of garlic (and could have added even more); doubled the amt. of parsley; and chopped coarsely the garlic cloves and the 1/2 cup onion. Used about 6 oz of large white mushrooms,sliced. 2) Sprinkled the ribs with plenty of salt and freshly-ground pepper, and browned them very thoroughly -- to dark brown but not burnt -- on all sides (about 8 min) with 2 Tbs canola oil in a large, heavy skillet at medium-high heat, then set ribs aside. 3) Drained all but about 2 Tbs of the resulting fat in the skillet, and SAUTEED the chopped onions until translucent, then added the chopped garlic and SAUTEED for another 2 minutes until onions were gold brown. Set sauteed onions and garlic aside. 4) In same skillet, I simmered the red wine on medium/high heat, scraping the fond from bottom of pan, until reduced to about 2/3 cup. 5) Used a 4 quart slow cooker (6 qt was too large). Transferred ribs to bottom of cooker. (The ribs were too large (~ 5") to fit in one even layer on bottom of cooker, but it turned out not to matter at all.) Added all remaining ingredients and cooked on low heat for 6 1/2 hours, then cooked on high heat for 1 more hour. The meat was incredibly tender -- could have cut it with a flimsy plastic fork -- and succulent beyond description. Didn't take the trouble to reduce or thicken the sauce (of which there was well more than enough), because it was delicious as is (though thin) and it smelled too good to wait a moment longer! (Would probably reduce/thicken it next time). Will never look for another recipe for braised ribs...can't imagine one better than this!

